author: @lhtd
text: Hey man !! Concerning the camera, as tons of people said, it's the lights and there are several ways of fixing it until you find one you like:  a) Dim the lights to make them more glossy and avoid those white reflections, thus lowering the contrast. You can use a sheet of paper or some cotton tissues like a t-shirt.  b) Make light more homogenous to diminish the contrast : Add a light source of light on your left. c) the space behind you has a very nice depth, but as the source of light is on one side, it is a green scale from bright to light. You can test recording on a more flat and homogeneous background. Test on a laptop and just sit with a wall flat behind you and you and you'll see what i mean.  For linux, probably the flickering things and maybe the delays come from the window managers. Try out some other window managers which might do the trick: XFCE, Mate, gnome, KDE or if you re feeling beautiful techy and adventurous, enlightment. You can install them from synaptic package manager or from your terminal. You can switch between any of them when you login into your session, there will be a small icon nearby your username. Click on it and switch from one to the other. My favourite ones are XFCE, mate and enlightment. They are quite good to manage different screens. My maximum has been 3, one of which was copy from one of my screens. Give it a shot, it should take you about 10 min to try.  Thanks for showing your computer, your experience is really appreciated. Concerning keyboards, I have a daskeyboard ten-keyless with mechanical brown switches. Good value for money to replace my old one.  Cheers and thanks !!!
